05193nam a22007575i 9780812293777DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984651807  a97808122937777 a10.9783/97808122937772doi  a(DE-B1597)481911  a(OCoLC)970632840  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a339.4/72231 aCohen, Joanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLuxurious Citizens :bThe Politics of Consumption in Nineteenth-Century America /cJoanna Cohen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b16 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerica in the Nineteenth Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Imagining the Citizen- Consumer -- tChapter 1. Dilemmas of Abundance -- tChapter 2. The Marketplace of Retribution -- tChapter 3. The Perils of the Public Auction -- tChapter 4. Of Tariffs and Taste -- tChapter 5. “They Now Advertise Liberally” -- tChapter 6. Consumers at War -- tEpilogue. The Citizen- Consumer and the State of the Nation -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the Revolution, Americans abandoned the political economy of self-denial and sacrifice that had secured their independence. In its place, they created one that empowered the modern citizen-consumer. This profound transformation was the uncoordinated and self-serving work of merchants, manufacturers, advertisers, auctioneers, politicians, and consumers themselves, who collectively created the nation's modern consumer economy: one that encouraged individuals to indulge their desires for the sake of the public good and cast the freedom to consume as a triumph of democracy. In Luxurious Citizens, Joanna Cohen traces the remarkable ways in which Americans tied consumer desire to the national interest between the end of the Revolution and the Civil War.Illuminating the links between political culture, private wants, and imagined economies, Cohen offers a new understanding of the relationship between citizens and the nation-state in nineteenth-century America. By charting the contest over economic rights and obligations in the United States, Luxurious Citizens argues that while many less powerful Americans helped to create the citizen-consumer it was during the Civil War that the Union government made use of this figure, by placing the responsibility for the nation's economic strength and stability on the shoulders of the people. Union victory thus enshrined a new civic duty in American life, one founded on the freedom to buy as you pleased. Reinterpreting the history of the tariff, slavery, and the coming of the Civil War through an examination of everyday acts of consumption and commerce, Cohen reveals the important ways in which nineteenth-century Americans transformed their individual desires for goods into an index of civic worth and fixed unbridled consumption at the heart of modern America's political economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aConsumption (Economics)zUnited States. 4aAmerican History. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229377740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293777423